  "name": "Morrison COU1 — CPB hemolysis credibility assessment (env-gap variant)",
  "description": "V&V 40 credibility assessment for CFD hemolysis prediction of the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump under cardiopulmonary bypass (CPB) conditions. COU1 evaluates whether the computational model can identify worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for a Class II CPB device at Model Risk Level 2. The pump is deployed in operating-room environments where ambient temperature ranges from 18°C to 26°C, electromagnetic interference from surgical equipment is present, and altitude-dependent ambient pressure varies between 95 kPa and 103 kPa. These environmental parameters influence blood viscosity, sensor signal fidelity, and motor control accuracy. All validation activities were conducted in a controlled laboratory at 22°C and standard atmospheric pressure; no environmental-sensitivity study characterising the effect of this operating envelope on model predictions has been performed or linked to this assessment.",
  "bindsRequirement": "https://uofa.net/synth/req/cpb-hemolysis-mrl2",
  "bindsClaim": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/cpb-hemolysis-rh-criterion",
  "bindsModel": "https://uofa.net/synth/model/fda-centrifugal-bp-cfd-v2",
  "bindsDataset": [
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-cbp-lab-validation-22degC",
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-cbp-geometry-nominal"
  ],
  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2. Deployment environments span hospital operating rooms at elevations up to 2 000 m, with ambient temperatures between 18°C and 26°C and electromagnetic interference from electrosurgical units and perfusion monitoring equipment. These conditions have not been characterised in the validation evidence base.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/cbp-bench-22degC-atm",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Bench validation — FDA centrifugal pump, 22°C, atmospheric pressure",
      "description": "Experimental hemolysis measurements collected using bovine blood analogue in a recirculating flow loop maintained at 22 ± 0.5°C and 101.3 kPa. Five flow-rate/rotational-speed operating points were tested. Normalised index of hemolysis (NIH) and relative hemolysis index (RH) were computed and compared against CFD predictions. All five operating points yielded RH < 1 relative to the predicate device. Tests were performed under constant fluorescent lighting with no electromagnetic shielding; no variation in ambient temperature, pressure, or EM environment was introduced during the test campaign."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/cbp-mesh-convergence-study",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Mesh convergence and discretisation error quantification",
      "description": "Grid convergence index (GCI) study performed on three systematically refined meshes (4.2 M, 11.7 M, and 31.4 M cells). GCI for the scalar shear-stress damage integral was 2.3% on the fine mesh, meeting the MRL 2 requirement. All simulations executed at 22°C blood viscosity (0.0035 Pa·s); no sensitivity of GCI to viscosity variation associated with temperature drift was evaluated."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/cbp-code-verification",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Numerical code verification — manufactured solution",
      "description": "Method of manufactured solutions (MMS) applied to the incompressible Navier–Stokes solver with power-law viscosity model. L2 error norms confirmed second-order spatial convergence. Verification conducted at a single nominal viscosity value corresponding to 22°C; temperature-dependent viscosity branches were not exercised in the MMS campaign."
    }
  ],
  "wasDerivedFrom": "https://doi.org/10.1115/1.4035258",
  "wasAttributedTo": "https://uofa.net/synth/org/morrison-lab-uofa",
