      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Second-order spatial convergence demonstrated via method of manufactured solutions for the governing transport equations.",
      "rationale": "MMS study confirmed second-order convergence in L2 norm for velocity and scalar damage integral fields. Conducted at nominal 22°C viscosity; temperature-dependent viscosity branches not separately verified, consistent with MRL 2 scope."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "GCI on the shear-stress damage integral below 5% on the production mesh.",
      "rationale": "Three-level GCI study yielded 2.3% on the 11.7 M-cell production mesh, satisfying the acceptance criterion. Study performed at fixed 22°C blood properties; no assessment of how ambient temperature variation alters viscosity and thereby discretisation error was conducted."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions documented with sufficient detail to reproduce experimental setup; temperature and pressure recorded at test time.",
      "rationale": "Laboratory conditions documented as 22 ± 0.5°C, 101.3 kPa, fluorescent lighting, no EM shielding. Conditions are internally consistent and reproducible within the laboratory. However, the documented conditions represent only a single point in the deployment environmental envelope (18–26°C, 95–103 kPa, variable EM). No characterisation of environmental sensitivity across the operating envelope is included in this evidence package."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (RH) reported for all five operating points with uncertainty bounds; RH < 1 for all points.",
      "rationale": "RH computed for all five flow-speed combinations. Values ranged from 0.71 to 0.94, all below the acceptance threshold of 1.0. Experimental uncertainty in NIH reported as ±8% (95% CI). Comparison performed exclusively at 22°C laboratory conditions; no output comparison at temperatures or pressures representative of the full deployment envelope."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI (normalised index of hemolysis, relative hemolysis index) directly maps to the clinical endpoint of pump-induced blood trauma.",
      "rationale": "NIH and RH are established regulatory QoIs for blood pump hemolysis assessment per FDA guidance. The mapping from shear-stress damage integral to clinical hemolysis is well-supported in literature. QoI relevance is independent of environmental conditions and is assessed as meeting level 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation geometry, fluid, and operating points match the COU device and intended flow-speed envelope.",
      "rationale": "Validation used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry at the five COU flow-speed combinations with bovine blood analogue of matched viscosity at 22°C. Geometry and flow conditions are directly relevant to the COU. The validation activities do not, however, span the environmental parameter space (temperature, pressure, EM) present in clinical deployment, representing a gap in coverage that is not acknowledged in the factor rationale."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual convergence below 1e-5 for all equations; mass imbalance below 0.01%.",
      "rationale": "All simulations converged to residuals below 1e-6 and mass imbalance below 0.005%. Solver error assessment is at the minimum required level for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup reviewed by a second analyst; boundary conditions and material properties documented.",
      "rationale": "Independent review of simulation setup performed by a second CFD analyst. Boundary conditions, turbulence model settings, and blood property inputs documented in the simulation report. Use error factor meets MRL 2 minimum."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Governing equations and constitutive models (turbulence, hemolysis power-law) justified for the flow regime and fluid.",
      "rationale": "SST k-ω turbulence model selected based on literature evidence for rotating blood pump flows. Giersiepen–Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model applied. Model form justified for Reynolds number range 2 000–18 000 encountered in the five operating points. Blood modelled as Newtonian at 22°C; shear-thinning effects at lower temperatures not assessed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Sensitivity of QoI to uncertain input parameters (geometry tolerances, viscosity, inlet velocity) quantified.",
      "rationale": "One-at-a-time sensitivity study conducted for impeller tip clearance (±0.05 mm), inlet flow rate (±2%), and blood viscosity at 22°C (±5%). Viscosity sensitivity at 22°C showed a 3.1% change in NIH per 5% viscosity change. Sensitivity to viscosity variation arising from the 18–26°C deployment temperature range (which would produce approximately 12% viscosity variation) was not evaluated, nor was sensitivity to ambient pressure or EM-induced motor speed perturbations."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test fluid properties characterised and traceable; pump specimen dimensions verified post-test.",
      "rationale": "Bovine blood analogue viscosity measured at 22°C with Brookfield viscometer prior to each test run. Pump specimen dimensions verified by CMM to within ±0.02 mm. Sample characterisation meets MRL 2 level 1 requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation input parameters match experimental conditions within stated tolerances for all five operating points.",
      "rationale": "CFD boundary conditions set to match measured laboratory flow rates, rotational speeds, and fluid viscosity at 22°C. Agreement between simulation inputs and experimental conditions confirmed within ±1.5% for all five operating points. Equivalency assessment is limited to the single laboratory temperature and pressure point; no equivalency mapping to the broader deployment environmental envelope is provided."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou1-env-gap-decision",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All seven assessed credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels for MRL 2. The six remaining factors are not assessed, which is acceptable at MRL 2 per ASME V&V 40-2018. The CFD model is accepted for use in identifying worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for the Class II CPB device. Validation evidence demonstrates RH < 1 across all five flow-speed combinations under laboratory conditions at 22°C and atmospheric pressure. The assessment team notes that deployment environments include operating rooms with temperature variation (18–26°C), altitude-dependent ambient pressure (95–103 kPa), and electromagnetic interference from surgical equipment; however, these environmental parameters were characterised only informally during team discussions and an environmental-sensitivity study was not formally conducted or linked to this evidence package. The team considers this acceptable given the medium model influence and the availability of physical testing to confirm results prior to clinical use.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
